Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button (on your page)

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2 & 3. Guard Navigation with Confirmation Dialog

In your **AppShell.xaml.cs**, override `OnNavigating` and use `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay" — cancel navigation

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

## 3. ViewModel Back Command

```csharp
// EditProductViewModel.cs
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Back()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating above, which handles the guard
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}

public bool HasUnsavedChanges { get; set; }
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it, navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- The guard fires for both the custom button *and* the system back gesture/hardware button, since both produce a `Pop` event.
